content.text:
Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me synthesize everything into a detailed implementation plan.

---

## Detailed Implementation Plan: Custom Theme System for T3 Code

### Design Decision Answers

**Question 1: How to integrate the new theme system with the existing `useTheme` hook?**

I recommend **option (a) with a careful migration path**: replace the existing hook to store a theme ID instead of `"light" | "dark" | "system"`, but model "system" as a separate concept -- a **preference**, not a theme.

The key insight is that the existing hook stores a *preference* (`"light" | "dark" | "system"`) while the new system stores a *theme selection* (`"t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight"`). These are orthogonal concerns. The cleanest architecture is:

- Store `themeId: string` in localStorage (replacing the old `"light" | "dark" | "system"` value)
- Add a **special** `"system"` value that means "auto-select between the light and dark defaults based on OS preference" -- this preserves the system preference behavior
- Each theme declares `mode: "light" | "dark"` in its metadata, so `resolvedTheme` continues to work identically
- When `themeId === "system"`, resolve to `"t3-light"` or `"t3-dark"` based on `prefers-color-scheme`

This approach means all 5 existing consumers of `resolvedTheme` continue to work with zero changes beyond the import path (which does not change since the hook stays at the same location). The settings page is the only place that needs significant UI changes.

**Backward compatibility for localStorage**: The existing key stores `"light" | "dark" | "system"`. We should handle migration: if the stored value is one of these legacy strings, map `"light"` to `"t3-light"`, `"dark"` to `"t3-dark"`, and `"system"` to `"system"`.

**Question 2: CSS custom properties strategy?**

I recommend a **hybrid of (b) and (c)**: The theme interface in `packages/shared` defines the 7 high-level color areas as the user-facing/editor-facing API, but *also* carries a full `cssProperties` map that contains all ~20 semantic CSS properties currently in `index.css`. The `applyTheme` function in the web app sets these on `document.documentElement.style`.

Rationale:
- The 7 high-level colors (background, foreground, accent, sidebar, editor, terminal, statusBar) serve as the "identity" of a theme -- good for theme previews, swatches, and the shared package API.
- The full CSS property map is necessary because the existing Tailwind system relies on `--background`, `--foreground`, `--primary`, `--border`, etc. These cannot all be derived from just 7 colors without a complex color algorithm.
- For built-in themes, we hardcode the full CSS property map. This keeps the existing visual fidelity identical.
- The `index.css` `:root` and `@variant dark` blocks remain as **fallbacks** -- they provide defaults when no theme has been JS-applied (initial page load before JS runs, SSR).

**Question 3: Backward compatibility with `resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark"`?**

Each theme declares `mode: "light" | "dark"`. The hook computes `resolvedTheme` from `theme.mode`, exactly as before. The "system" preference resolves to a specific theme first, then that theme's mode determines `resolvedTheme`. This means:
- `resolvedTheme` remains `"light" | "dark"` always
- `resolveDiffThemeName(resolvedTheme)` continues to work
- `document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", ...)` continues to work
- `ComposerPromptEditor.resolvedThemeFromDocument()` continues to work (it reads the `.dark` class)

---

### File-by-File Implementation Plan

#### 1. NEW FILE: `packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

This is the shared, pure TypeScript theme registry. It follows the exact same pattern as `packages/shared/src/model.ts` -- pure exported functions, no side effects, no DOM access.

```typescript
// Theme color palette -- the 7 identity colors for previews/swatches
export interface ThemeColors {
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  accent: string;
  sidebar: string;
  editor: string;
  terminal: string;
  statusBar: string;
}

// Full CSS custom property overrides that map to the existing Tailwind system
export interface ThemeCSSProperties {
  "--background": string;
  "--foreground": string;
  "--card": string;
  "--card-foreground": string;
  "--popover": string;
  "--popover-foreground": string;
  "--primary": string;
  "--primary-foreground": string;
  "--secondary": string;
  "--secondary-foreground": string;
  "--muted": string;
  "--muted-foreground": string;
  "--accent": string;
  "--accent-foreground": string;
  "--destructive": string;
  "--destructive-foreground": string;
  "--border": string;
  "--input": string;
  "--ring": string;
  "--info": string;
  "--info-foreground": string;
  "--success": string;
  "--success-foreground": string;
  "--warning": string;
  "--warning-foreground": string;
}

export interface Theme {
  readonly id: string;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly mode: "light" | "dark";
  readonly colors: ThemeColors;
  readonly fontFamily?: string;
  readonly fontSize?: number;
  readonly cssProperties: ThemeCSSProperties;
}
```

Define 3 built-in themes:
- `"t3-dark"`: The existing dark theme values from `@variant dark` in `index.css`, translated to concrete color strings. The `colors` field picks representative values for the 7 areas from the existing dark palette.
- `"t3-light"`: The existing light `:root` values from `index.css`. Same approach.
- `"t3-midnight"`: A new deeper/richer dark theme with distinct accent colors (perhaps a blue-shifted dark with higher contrast).

Export functions:
- `getTheme(id: string): Theme | undefined` -- look up by ID
- `listThemes(): readonly Theme[]` -- return all built-in themes
- `getDefaultThemeId(): string` -- returns `"t3-dark"`
- `resolveThemeId(id: string | null | undefined): string` -- returns the ID if valid, or the default

The `cssProperties` values for `t3-dark` and `t3-light` must exactly reproduce the current CSS custom property values from `index.css`. For the oklch/color-mix values, use the same CSS expressions as strings -- they will be set via `document.documentElement.style.setProperty()` and the browser will resolve them. This is important: we are not computing final RGB values in JS, we are setting CSS property values that may contain `color-mix()`, `oklch()`, `var()` etc.

However, there is a subtlety: the current CSS uses Tailwind `--color-*` variables (e.g., `var(--color-white)`, `var(--color-neutral-800)`) which are defined by Tailwind at build time. When we set properties via JS, these references will still resolve correctly because the Tailwind `@theme` block defines them. So the theme's `cssProperties` can use the same expressions.

#### 2. MODIFY: `packages/shared/package.json`

Add a new subpath export:
```json
"./themes": {
  "types": "./src/themes.ts",
  "import": "./src/themes.ts"
}
```

This follows the existing pattern for `./model`, `./git`, etc.

#### 3. NEW FILE: `packages/shared/src/themes.test.ts`

Unit tests following the pattern in `model.test.ts`:
- `getTheme("t3-dark")` returns the dark theme with `mode: "dark"`
- `getTheme("t3-light")` returns the light theme with `mode: "light"`
- `getTheme("t3-midnight")` returns the midnight theme with `mode: "dark"`
- `getTheme("nonexistent")` returns `undefined`
- `listThemes()` returns all 3 themes
- `resolveThemeId(null)` returns the default
- Each theme's `cssProperties` has all required keys

#### 4. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`

This is the most critical file. The rewrite preserves the `useSyncExternalStore` architecture but extends the stored state from a simple `"light" | "dark" | "system"` string to a theme ID.

Key changes:

**Storage**: Same localStorage key `"t3code:theme"` but now stores a theme ID string (`"t3-dark"`, `"t3-light"`, `"t3-midnight"`, or `"system"`).

**Migration**: The `getStored()` function detects legacy values:
```typescript
function getStored(): string {
  const raw = localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY);
  if (!raw) return "system";
  // Legacy migration
  if (raw === "light") return "t3-light";
  if (raw === "dark") return "t3-dark";
  if (raw === "system") return "system";
  // New theme ID
  return raw;
}
```

**Theme resolution**: New function `resolveThemeFromPreference(preference: string)`:
- If `preference === "system"`: pick `"t3-light"` or `"t3-dark"` based on `getSystemDark()`
- Otherwise: look up via `getTheme(preference)` from `@t3tools/shared/themes`; if not found, fall back to `getTheme(getDefaultThemeId())`

**`applyTheme` rewrite**: Instead of just toggling `.dark`, it also sets CSS custom properties:
```typescript
function applyTheme(theme: Theme, suppressTransitions = false) {
  if (suppressTransitions) { /* same no-transitions logic */ }

  const isDark = theme.mode === "dark";
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", isDark);
  document.documentElement.style.setProperty("color-scheme", isDark ? "dark" : "light");

  // Apply all CSS custom properties from the theme
  for (const [prop, value] of Object.entries(theme.cssProperties)) {
    document.documentElement.style.setProperty(prop, value);
  }

  // Apply font family if specified
  if (theme.fontFamily) {
    document.body.style.fontFamily = theme.fontFamily;
  }

  if (suppressTransitions) { /* same cleanup */ }
}
```

**Snapshot type change**:
```typescript
type ThemeSnapshot = {
  themeId: string;       // The stored preference: "system" | theme ID
  resolvedTheme: Theme;  // The resolved Theme object
  systemDark: boolean;
};
```

**Hook return type** -- maintain backward compatibility while extending:
```typescript
export function useTheme() {
  const snapshot = useSyncExternalStore(subscribe, getSnapshot);

  const resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark" = snapshot.resolvedTheme.mode;

  const setTheme = useCallback((next: string) => {
    localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, next);
    const resolved = resolveThemeFromPreference(next);
    applyTheme(resolved, true);
    emitChange();
  }, []);

  return {
    theme: snapshot.themeId,            // "system" | theme ID (was "light" | "dark" | "system")
    setTheme,                           // now accepts theme ID or "system"
    resolvedTheme,                      // "light" | "dark" -- UNCHANGED TYPE
    currentTheme: snapshot.resolvedTheme, // NEW: the full Theme object
    availableThemes: listThemes(),       // NEW: for theme selectors
  } as const;
}
```

The `theme` property type broadens from `"light" | "dark" | "system"` to `string`. This is a **widening**, which means existing code that reads `theme` (only the settings page) will still compile. The settings page is the only consumer that reads `theme` (to highlight the selected option), and it will be rewritten anyway.

The `setTheme` parameter type broadens from `Theme` (the old type alias for `"light" | "dark" | "system"`) to `string`. Again, this is safe because all callers pass string literals.

**`resolvedTheme`** stays exactly `"light" | "dark"`, so all 5 consumers work with zero changes.

#### 5. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/index.css`

Minimal changes. The `:root` and `@variant dark` blocks remain as they are. They serve as the initial/fallback values before JS runs. Once `applyTheme` executes, the inline style properties on `<html>` take precedence over the CSS custom properties in the stylesheet (because inline style custom properties have higher specificity than stylesheet custom properties in the same selector).

Wait -- actually, that is not quite right. CSS custom property specificity is determined by the selector, not inline vs stylesheet for custom properties set via `style.setProperty`. Let me reconsider.

Actually, `document.documentElement.style.setProperty("--background", value)` sets an inline style on `<html>`, which is the same element targeted by `:root`. Inline styles have higher specificity than any selector, so the inline custom property values will override the `:root` block values. And for the `@variant dark` block, those properties are also on `:root` (just within a `.dark` selector context via `@custom-variant`), so the inline styles will still take precedence.

This means the CSS stays as-is, and the JS-applied theme properties cleanly override them. The only change to `index.css`: optionally add the `color-scheme` property to the `:root` block if not already there (it is already there at line 65).

One additional consideration: the `body` font-family. If the theme specifies `fontFamily`, the `applyTheme` function sets `body.style.fontFamily`. The CSS `body { font-family: "DM Sans", ... }` will be overridden by the inline style. For themes that do not specify `fontFamily`, we should not set or should clear the inline font-family so the CSS default applies.

No changes needed to `index.css`.

#### 6. NEW FILE: `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`

A new component for the settings page that replaces the current radio-button theme selector. This component shows theme preview swatches.

Design approach:
- Grid of theme cards (similar visual pattern to the existing radio-button list but with color swatches)
- Each card shows:
  - Theme name
  - A miniature preview swatch showing the theme's key colors (background, foreground, accent, sidebar colors as small colored rectangles/circles)
  - Selected state indicator (matching the existing `border-primary/60 bg-primary/8` pattern)
- A separate "System" toggle/option at the top (since "system" is not a theme but a preference)
- Uses `useTheme()` to get `theme`, `setTheme`, and `availableThemes`

The component structure:

```tsx
function ThemeSelector() {
  const { theme, setTheme, availableThemes, resolvedTheme } = useTheme();
  const isSystem = theme === "system";

  return (
    <div>
      {/* System preference toggle */}
      <button onClick={() => setTheme("system")} aria-checked={isSystem}>
        System (auto) - currently {resolvedTheme}
      </button>

      {/* Theme grid */}
